         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">The Camp ¶ Sunningdale Oct 3d /86 ¶ My dear Baron ¶  ¶ I thank you exceedingly for the gift of your splendid volume on  ¶ Myoporineae ¶  which will add a huge corner stone to the edifice you have rais...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">86.10.03b</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M3, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">.<space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS annotation by M: 'Answ 2/12/86'. Letter not found.</p>
               </note>The Camp</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Sunningdale Oct 3d /86</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Baron</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I thank you exceedingly for the gift of your splendid volume on <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Myoporineae">Myoporineae</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> which will add a huge corner stone to the edifice you have raised to Australian Botany. It is a capital pair to the Eucalypts &amp; I can hope now that your labors will be carried on for many years to come.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I have also to thank you for your many kind attentions to my son Brian, who seems to be getting on well, though it is now a good many weeks since I have heard from him.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I occupy Bentham's room &amp; table at Kew, &amp; pretty much confine my labors to the Indian Flora,<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. Hooker (1875-97).</p>
               </note> of which the last part went to you a month or two ago</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I find certain Orders to be very hard &amp; very unsatisfactory work. Especially <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Laurineae">Laurineae</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Myristiceae">Myristiceae</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> &amp; <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Piperaceae">Piperaceae</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>, none of which trouble you much in Australia. I am now working at <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Phyllanthus">Phyllanthus</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg> which requires a thorough revision. I have many new species of the <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">
                     <name key="Bradleia">Bradleia</name>
                  </hi>
               </seg>section, but not many of others.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Though working so near to the Gardens I see very little of them having no time to spare from my Herbarium work.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Dr Aitchison<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>J. E. T. Aitchison.</p>
               </note> is here naming his plants of the Affghan Boundary Commission. Reichenbach has also been at Kew, at Orchids of course.</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Very sincerely yr</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Jos D Hooker</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
